text.b: Clive Town Center Traffic Impact Study

page.text: Snyder & Associates has completed an assessment and analyzed the potential traffic impacts
associated with new land use and redevelopment per the proposed Clive Town Center Vision
The City of Clive is moving forward with the next stage of concept design for the development
and redevelopment plans outlined in the Clive Town Center Vision Plan, June 2013 as prepared
by Reynolds Urban Design. The plan includes redevelopment of existing office area and
development of a living/working community with civic, office, retail, and residential mix use
parcels along with the development of vacant parcel for general offices, multi-family residential,
and small retail development. Access to all development will be to/from NW 114
including the town center which is adjacent to NW 114
The analysis included existing conditions and trip generation, projected development traffic for
Initial Build of the Town Center (year 2018), and Complete Build of the entire area (2030)
Traffic has remained relatively constant within the corridor between University Avenue and
Hickman Road for the past 10 year period. The initial build of the Town Center land use plan
will generate approximately 4,840 net new vehicle trips per day, and 300 net new vehicle trips
per hour (vph) in the PM peak hour of the typical weekday. The overall number of net new trips
generated per complete build of Town Center Vision Plan will be 7,930 vpd, and 810 vph.
In comparison the complete build of the Town Center Vision Plan for the entire NW 114
corridor will generate approximately 4,700 vpd, or 570 vph trips above the current adopted
comprehensive land use plan and existing land uses.
Between Clark Street and Walnut Creek, the complete build out of the overall Town Center
Vision Plan area could result in an approximate 55-62% increase in daily traffic volume and a
48-62% increase in peak hour traffic volume based on current trip generation trends of proposed
land use. In comparison a complete build out of the current Comprehensive Land Use Plan
could result in an approximate 25-36% increase in daily traffic volume and a 15-43% increase in
peak hour traffic volume in the same area between Clark Street and Walnut Creek.
Given current established traffic patterns approximately 30% of this traffic will travel to/from
Hickman Rd, 65% will travel to/from University Avenue, and 5% or less will travel to/from
Street between Walnut Creek and Clark Street is
proposed to remain as a two lane, and be narrowed in the vicinity of the Town Center to create
more urban environment, and provide for diagonal parking. The projected traffic volumes within
this area of 800 to 1,100 vph, during the initial build of Town Center to complete build out of the
area per the plan can be accommodated with this type of street network. The diagonal parking
will create additional conflict within this area, but will also develop a mitigating effect of slower
traffic speeds. New trips associated with the initial build of the Town Center will create
marginal increases in delay at the key intersections at either end of the corridor with University
Avenue and Hickman Road and not require additional roadway infrastructure.
The study concluded that no immediate improvements along NW 114
due to Initial Build of the Town Center traffic conditions.
If the complete build of the Vision Plan for land use in the entire area is realized, delay increase
will be encountered at Hickman Road intersection, and on NW 114
University Avenue. As traffic volumes increase with complete build conditions in the corridor,
traffic conditions should be monitored since analysis shows unacceptable vehicle delay will be
experienced during the PM peak period for two gateway intersections at Hickman Road and
University Avenue, Clark Street, and South Campus Drive.
Capacity improvements or changes in traffic control at these intersections may be needed if
excessive delay is experienced during other hours of the day besides analyzed PM peak hour
delay. Additional roadway capacity through widening is difficult to achieve due to tight right of
way and existing land development. The City will need to continue long range planning efforts
to look for overall intersection improvements at Hickman Road and University Avenue in
partnership with neighboring communities and/or the Iowa DOT, and seek opportunities through
redevelopment to secure right of way or other circulation streets and drives for improved traffic

Street traffic has been at a stable level for the past 8-10 years, further a comparison of

total traffic generation characteristics approximately equal to the actual traffic demand totals.
From this comparison and review of the traffic volume patterns and demands minimizing at the

Street’s actual use as a “through street”, or rather for traffic that has no origin or
destination within the corridor but just drives directly from University to Hickman (or reversed)
is a relatively low amount, less than 20%.

Capacity analysis analyzes and describes the performance of study intersections and roadways
under various traffic volumes and traffic control scenarios. For this study, intersection capacity
was analyzed for existing conditions Year 2013, Initial Build Year 2018, and Complete Build
Year 2030 for all intersections within the study corridor per Highway Capacity Manual
methodology incorporated into the traffic analysis and modeling program, Synchro8. The Noon
and PM peak hours are evaluated for each analysis scenario.
Intersection delay, caused by traffic volume, turning vehicles, number of lanes, arrival patterns,
etc. is qualitatively described by a performance measure called ‘Level of Service’ (LOS), which
‘grades’ delay on a scale of A-F. LOS A is considered the most desirable level, with the least
delay, while LOS F is least desirable, with the most delay. LOS criteria defined by the HCM for
signalized and unsignalized intersections are shown in Table 5.
The results of the Capacity Analysis LOS for critical movements are summarized in Table 6 for

text.b: Traffic Features of the Town Center

page.text: The most current update to the Town Center development plan per Reynolds Urban Design is
shown in Figure 4. Unique transportation features proposed for the Town Center include:
Street will remain a two lane street, but have a narrower pavement width, 24 feet,
with angle parking from north of Mercy medical parking lot to south of the Aquatic Center
driveway. The anticipated traffic volumes for peak hour are within the capacity of this type
of roadway design. The introduction of angle parking does create additional conflicts for
property damage type crashes, however the narrower pavement width, and parking activity
can create a mitigating “traffic calming” effect by slowing traffic down through the area.
This is helpful given the natural downgrade northbound and driver’s common increase in
speed through the area. It is assumed that this area may have a 25-30 mph posted speed limit
continued further south from the current zone near Walnut Creek. (Some local and out of
state comparable examples of urban street corridors with two lanes and on street parking are
2. Angle Parking is planned along NW 114
Street. It will be important to verify minimum
corner clearances for sight distance at the existing business driveways along the west side of
Street, and for the connection points of the Campus Drive one way pair on either
side of the civic plaza area south of the proposed civic building. Angle parking will also
need to be checked for a minimum clear distance of 20-25’ near crosswalks for proper sight
distance of crossing pedestrians to oncoming NW 114
3. A one way circulating pair of streets is proposed for the civic plaza area to provide vehicular
traffic access, yet create a traffic calming effect for the mix with a pedestrian oriented
environment. Again, minimum setback distance from intersections for parking backing
maneuvers and sight distance for vehicle or pedestrians will be important to this design.
Further, street layout will need to consider City public works maintenance and emergency
service vehicle turning paths, and further trash hauler type vehicles as well for turning ability
to avoid wheel encroachment on curbs and sidewalk areas. The one way, north street pair for
WB traffic should be adequately served with STOP control at NW 114
4. Potential “speed tables” for the pedestrian crosswalks on NW 114
discussed. The City should give careful consideration to the proposed narrow street width
and angle parking and that may have enough “traffic calming effect” that speed tables at
crossings may not be necessary. Given potential traffic volume and likely density of
pedestrians it may be important to consider these at only a few locations in the corridor such
as the north end near Aquatic Center Drive and south end near the mixed use building. They
could serve at these locations as an “entry feature” or reminder for drivers of the slower
speed and possible conflicts. The other option would be to place on either side of the Civic
Plaza given the potential for pedestrian interaction in this area.
5. Given the angle parking, and design for more pedestrian activity, careful consideration and
layout should be made with roadway lighting through the corridor. Typical MidAmerican
street lighting may not provide the uniformity desired through the corridor, in addition to the
issues with greater setback of light poles from the street with parking insets. Further goals of
pedestrian walk area lighting in combination with the roadway lighting may require unique

3. Monitor intersections and perform regular traffic counts as development proceeds to
determine when traffic levels warrant consideration of changes in traffic control.
a. Traffic signalization at the intersection of Clark Street could be possible with
increased traffic volumes in future years. Additional considerations for traffic
signalization include driver’s decision complexities due to intersection skew, site
distance due to obstructions in median, vehicle turning path time (time to make
turning maneuver due to intersection width). Pending total pavement reconstruction
needs, a roundabout could be another option for the Clark intersection as an efficient
means to handle peak hour traffic, yet minimize delay in non peak hours. This could
prove beneficial to access for the developments north of Forest Avenue as well and
serve as a traffic calming approach to create the transition to the more pedestrian
friendly and narrower corridor with diagonal parking being proposed for the Town
b. Traffic control needs at South Campus Drive to “Park Neighborhood” housing

Street during peak hours. Likewise potential for a
roundabout at this intersection could serve traffic needs in peak hours, minimize
delays in off peak times, and serve with the traffic calming issues.
4. Clark Street will require continued monitoring of traffic volumes during peak hours to avoid

5. A complete build out of the current adopted Comprehensive Plan (existing vacant parcels)
